I"e<p>The debate on the feasibility of remote work lingers on 3 years after the pandemic started. Companies are still bouncing back-and-forth between return to office (RTO) and remote work like an indecisive child crying and unsure whether he’s hungry or just bored. The nature of work is a <a href="https://www.interaction-design.org/literature/topics/wicked-problems#:~:text=A%20wicked%20problem%20is%20a%20social%20or%20cultural%20problem%20that's,attempts%20to%20find%20a%20solution.">wicked problem</a> because it touches upon the complex root of how humans fundamentally communicate and collaborate. As I read more and more articles about the debate in this topic, I start to question whether this is a technological or an user experience (UX) issue.</p>

<p>Solving remote work is too wide a scope to tackle in one go, so let’s narrow this discussion on just redesigning the video meeting experience. Let’s highlight some of the problems with current tools, then we’ll reimagine what a more smooth and productive video meeting experience could be like, and how both AI and better UX can make that a reality.</p>

